            <h2>Subjunctive</h2>
            <p><span class="initial-letter darkorange-text">T</span>he <strong>subjunctive</strong> mood is used to express wishes,
                desires, or outcomes that are dependent on certain conditions being met. In modern English, a series of constructs
                utilising 'if' clauses and different tenses and modal verbs are used to express the conditional. Using these constructs we can say anything
                from 'if it rains, I will cry' to the complex 'if I had studied more, I would have passed the exam'.
                </p>
                <p>There are also a few examples of different verb forms being used to form conditionals in modern English. 
                'If I <em>were</em> fluent in Old English' is expressing a desire using a different form of the verb 'to be' than the expected 
                first person past 'If I was'. 'We suggest that he <em>be</em> excused' is another example, again in rather formal English.
                The subjunctive also survives in archaic expressions such as 'long live the king', the form 'live' is used rather than 
                the third person 'lives' because it is expressing a desire - <em>may</em> this person live long; the same is true of 
                'Glory <em>be</em> to God': the subjunctive <em>be</em> is used to express a desire.
            </p>
            <p>In Old English subjunctive forms of verbs are far more common. As with <strong>imperatives</strong>, there is one subjunctive form of
                a verb for singular and one for plural, so there are only two new forms to learn. The singular
                form is the root of the verb with <strong>-e </strong>added, and the plural form is the root of the verb with <strong>-en</strong>- added. Examine the sentences
                below, '<em>Gif heo to Rome fare - If she would travel to Rome</em>' and '<em>þæt ge þa sang hieren - That ye might hear the 
                song</em>'.
            </p>
