            <p>In first person present singular and first and third person past it can be hard to distinguish a subjunctive form from the usual 
                indicative -e ending. However, the context will usually make it clear that a condition, or a counterfactual statement is being made.
                Sentences opening with '<e,>gif - if</e>' or '<em>butan - unless</em>' or '<em>þeah - though/although</em>' are usually expressing 
                a condition, and we would expect a subjunctive form to be used. Similarly, a subjunctive is required after the use of the verb 
                '<em>willian - to wish</em>', as this is expressing a desire.
            </p>
            <p>
                However, there are also places where a subjunctive is used when no desire or condition is expressed. For example, it is often found when
                reporting something that was said, or following a verb of command. In many cases it is appropriate
                to translate these sentences with modal verbs such as 'should/would/could/might' in modern English, but sometimes the normal indicative
                form is fine. Examine the sentence below: '<em>Odda het ðæt he come to him</em>' which uses the singular subjunctive <em>come</em> with it's 
                <strong>-e</strong> ending, and is perhaps best translated 'Odda ordered that he <em>should</em> come to him'.
            </p>
